  <dashboards>
    <dashboard enable-sort-zone-taborder='true' name='Conclusion'>
      <style />
      <size maxheight='800' maxwidth='1000' minheight='800' minwidth='1000' />
      <zones>
        <zone h='100000' id='12' type-v2='layout-basic' w='100000' x='0' y='0'>
          <zone forceUpdate='true' h='49000' id='11' type-v2='text' w='98400' x='800' y='1000'>
            <formatted-text>
              <run bold='true' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='22'>Conclusion</run>
              <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
              <run fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='12'>Overall, housing affordability changed unevenly across the United States between 2010 and 2024. By combining Census income data, Census rent data, FRED inflation data, and BLS labor market data, we created a merged dataset that allowed us to compare affordability across states more accurately.</run>
              <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
              <run fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='12'>The main takeaway is that rent burden increased in many states, meaning rent took up a larger share of income in 2024 than it did in 2010. States such as Nevada, Colorado, Arizona, and Texas showed some of the largest declines in affordability, while states like Vermont, Mississippi, and Arkansas remained more stable or improved slightly.</run>
              <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
              <run fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='12'>This project also showed why inflation adjustment matters. Without adjusting 2010 values into 2024 dollars, the comparison would be misleading. Our final dashboard helps show where affordability pressures were most severe and supports the broader conclusion that housing affordability is not changing equally across the country.</run>
            </formatted-text>
            <zone-style>
              <format attr='border-color' value='#000000' />
              <format attr='border-style' value='none' />
              <format attr='border-width' value='0' />
              <format attr='margin' value='4' />
            </zone-style>
          </zone>
          <zone forceUpdate='true' h='49000' id='13' type-v2='text' w='98400' x='800' y='50000'>
            <formatted-text>
              <run bold='true' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='15'>Key Takeaways</run>
              <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
              <run fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='12'>• Rent burden increased in many states from 2010 to 2024.</run>
              <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
              <run fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='12'>• Western and Sunbelt states experienced some of the largest affordability declines.</run>
              <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
              <run fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='12'>• Some Midwest and rural states remained more stable.</run>
              <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
              <run fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='12'>• Inflation adjustment was necessary to compare 2010 and 2024 values fairly.</run>
              <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
              <run fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='12'>• Housing affordability trends vary widely by state.</run>
            </formatted-text>
            <zone-style>
              <format attr='border-color' value='#000000' />
              <format attr='border-style' value='none' />
              <format attr='border-width' value='0' />
              <format attr='margin' value='4' />
            </zone-style>
          </zone>
          <zone-style>
            <format attr='border-color' value='#000000' />
            <format attr='border-style' value='none' />
            <format attr='border-width' value='0' />
            <format attr='margin' value='8' />
          </zone-style>
        </zone>
      </zones>
      <devicelayouts>
        <devicelayout auto-generated='true' name='Phone'>
          <size maxheight='700' minheight='700' sizing-mode='vscroll' />
          <zones>
            <zone h='100000' id='17' type-v2='layout-basic' w='100000' x='0' y='0'>
              <zone h='98000' id='16' param='vert' type-v2='layout-flow' w='98400' x='800' y='1000'>
                <zone forceUpdate='true' h='49000' id='11' type-v2='text' w='98400' x='800' y='1000'>
                  <formatted-text>
                    <run bold='true' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='22'>Conclusion</run>
                    <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
                    <run fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='12'>Overall, housing affordability changed unevenly across the United States between 2010 and 2024. By combining Census income data, Census rent data, FRED inflation data, and BLS labor market data, we created a merged dataset that allowed us to compare affordability across states more accurately.</run>
                    <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
                    <run fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='12'>The main takeaway is that rent burden increased in many states, meaning rent took up a larger share of income in 2024 than it did in 2010. States such as Nevada, Colorado, Arizona, and Texas showed some of the largest declines in affordability, while states like Vermont, Mississippi, and Arkansas remained more stable or improved slightly.</run>
                    <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
                    <run fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='12'>This project also showed why inflation adjustment matters. Without adjusting 2010 values into 2024 dollars, the comparison would be misleading. Our final dashboard helps show where affordability pressures were most severe and supports the broader conclusion that housing affordability is not changing equally across the country.</run>
                  </formatted-text>
                  <zone-style>
                    <format attr='border-color' value='#000000' />
                    <format attr='border-style' value='none' />
